Communications

AX.25

First Bit Sent
Flag Address Control PID Info. FCS Flag
01111110 112/560 Bits 8 Bits 8 Bits N*8 Bits 16 Bits 01111110
Information frame construction
Source: https://tapr.org/pub_ax25.html

Flag Field

Defines the beginning and the end of the frame.

Address Field

Defines the source and the destination of the frame.

Control Field

Defines the type of frame.

PID Field

Protocol Identifier (PID) identifies the layer 3 protocol, if any are in use.

Information Field

Used for the user data (packet standard is 64 bytes long), 3 types are available:

  • I frame: up to 256 octets long
  • UI frame
  • FRMR frame

Frame-Check Sequence

16 bits to check for frame corruption. [ISO 3309 (HDLC)]

Getting Started

Use the following steps:

  • Download and install Arduino IDE. https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software
  • Download and install Seeeduino v4 Drivers. http://wiki.seeedstudio.com/Seeeduino_v4.2/
  • Download and install ArduSatSDK on Arduino IDE. https://github.com/ArduSat/ArduSatSDK
  • Download and install XCTU from digi.com for Wireless Modules. https://www.digi.com/products/iot-platform/xctu
  • Start coding on Arduino IDE in the Arduino programming language.

Next Steps

  • Send commands and receive responses.
  • Use Python with Arduino.
    • Assemble AX.25 Packet
    • Assemble CSP Packet

Antennas

A half-wave dipole antenna receiving a radio signal. The incoming radio wave (whose electric field is shown as E, green arrows) causes an oscillating electric current within the antenna elements (black arrows), alternately charging the two sides of the antenna positively (+) and negatively (−). Since the antenna is one half a wavelength long at the radio wave's frequency, the voltage (shown as V, red bands) and current in the antenna form a standing wave. This oscillating current flows down the antenna's transmission line through the radio receiver (represented by resistor R).

435Mhz is almost 70cm

The Plan

  • Getting one VM up and running.
  • Making it communicate with itself via LAN.
  • Learn to assemble AX.25 packets (GNU Radio should help).
  • Get it to create/send/recieve AX.25 Packets (also via LAN or files).
  • Get it to read and and respond to specific commands.
  • Get another VM running and make it communicate with the first one.
  • Have a simple web interface running to show the packets being sent and received.
  • Setup physcial raspberry pi to communicate with the ground station directly.
